 Orleans will disappear; many nuclear and other power plants, hundreds of wastewater plants and toxic waste sites, and oil production facilities will be at risk; port infrastructures will need to be raised; and over ten million Americans fleeing rising seas will become climate refugees. In Sea Level Rise Orrin H. Pilkey and Keith C. Pilkey argue that the only feasible response along much of the U.S. shoreline is an immediate and managed retreat. Among many topics, they examine sea level rise's effects on coastal ecosystems, health, and native Alaskan coastal communities. They also provide guidelines for those living on the coasts or planning on moving to or away from them, as well as the steps local governments should take to prepare for this unstoppable, impending catastrophe.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Sep 2020) 0aClimatic changesxEconomic aspectszUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxHealth aspectszUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxPolitical aspectszUnited States. 0aClimatic changesxSocial aspectszUnited States. 0aEnvironmental refugeeszUnited States. 0aFlood insurancezUnited States. 0aSea levelzUnited States. 0aShore protectionzUnited States. 7aNATURE / Environmental Conservation & Protection.2bisacsh1 aPilkey, Keith C., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2019z978311069632540uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781478005124zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781478005124423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781478005124.jpg  a978-3-11-069632-5  DUK eBook-Package 2019b2019  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles